<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26269f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26269f">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26269f"> 269(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> numinal</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Household worship]</font>&mdash;The household is thus at once the logical starting-point of religious cult, and throughout Roman history the centre of its more real and vital activity. The head of the house (<i>paterfamilias</i>) is the natural priest and has control of the domestic worship: he is assisted by his sons as acolytes (<i>camilli</i>) and deputes certain portions of the ritual to his wife and daughters and even to his bailiff (<i>vicilus</i>) and his bailiff&apos;s wife. The worship centres round certain <i><mark>numina</mark></i>, the spirits indwelling in the sacred places of the original round hut in which the family lived. <small> &ldquo;ROMAN RELIGION&rdquo; <a name="EBRR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRR"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 577</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
